knowledge_graph.title: Yojimbo
knowledge_graph.description: A nameless ronin, or samurai with no master (Toshirô Mifune), enters a small village in feudal Japan where two rival businessmen are struggling for control of the local gambling trade. Taking the name Sanjuro Kuwabatake, the ronin convinces both silk merchant Tazaemon (Kamatari Fujiwara) and sake merchant Tokuemon (Takashi Shimura) to hire him as a personal bodyguard, then artfully sets in motion a full-scale gang war between the two ambitious and unscrupulous men.… MORE

related_questions.question: What does Yojimbo mean in Japanese?

related_questions.question: What does Sanjuro mean in Kuwabatake?
related_questions.snippet: In both movies, Mifune says that he's called Sanjuro, which means “30 years old,” and quips, “going on 40.” He also tacks on a name inspired by whatever vegetation is nearest: In Yojimbo, he's Sanjuro “Kuwabatake” (“mulberry field”); in Sanjuro, he's Sanjuro “Tsubaki” (“camellia”).
related_questions.title: mulberry field
